50|$|Leslie Regan Shade {{argues that}} <b>the</b> human <b>right</b> <b>to</b> <b>privacy</b> is {{necessary}} for meaningful democratic participation, and ensures human dignity and autonomy. Privacy depends on norms for how information is distributed, {{and if this is}} appropriate. Violations of privacy depend on context. <b>The</b> human <b>right</b> <b>to</b> <b>privacy</b> has precedent in the United Nations Declaration of Human Rights. Shade believes that privacy must be approached from a people-centered perspective, and not through the marketplace.|$|R
